Okay more serious response
I kinda blazed through the doc so i may have missed some details

This is a seriously cool setting. I am very much digging the apocalyptic setting, and I'm really fascinated by desert dwelling peoples. I'm guessing you've read Dune, which is a favorite of mine. That seems to be the inspiration for the land scubas, but if you haven't read it, you will definitely find it a useful source of inspiration for water-discipline and desert ecology.

Re causes, you seem to have a direction for them, but honestly, I think you could get away with omitting specific details. You could leave a lot of humanity's records as being lost, which would also explain why certain technologies appear to be abandoned or forgotten; no one knows how to make or operate it anymore.
That said, from my loose understanding of meteorology, it sounds like the Earth's atmosphere has thinned dramatically. So there's a much greater level of UV exposure across the planet, more heat going into the oceans, and that drives increased evaporation worldwide.We already had a scare with chlorofluorocarbons, and if we didn't learn our lesson from those, it's not much of a stretch to say that we would have ravaged our planet's protections.

Peyote is absolutely a great choice for a recreational drug though, and it definitely makes sense to have it as THE drug of choice. I really like it's incorporation into existing religions, with a different layer of meaning added for each one.

A couple questions I'm curious about:
Is rice incorporated into any of the aquaponics setups? You may have already researched this, so maybe it wouldn't make for a very useful crop for one reason or another.
Have you considered geothermal energy sources in this setting? I could see the cylinder cities being in a good position to take advantage of it, but I also understand that you may want to keep the influence of technology lesser.

actual response, since I wanted to repsond to all the bigen posts first
I haven't read dune, but I do have a general idea of what happened. I was gonna, but then the movie came out and demotivated me
Land scubas are actually just something I thought would enrich the setting, and I also wanted a way to limit travel.
The causes are more of a reason for the audience, but yeah I think I agree with that. I didn't really have anything set out other than general pollution and industry. I don't want to make a bunch of fantasy stuff and magic in the setting, but i'm a little less worried about if the setting requires you to suspend your disbelief a bit in order to actually be created in the first place.
Either way, it's still cool it's hypothetically possible.
Thanks for the peyote thing. Some people tell me it seems excessive or they "dont like the drugs thing", but I think that speaks less to the work itself
As for rice, I don't see a reason it COULDNT be in setups. I mean the specific crops are gonna vary by location and whatnot, but rice seems reasonable.
Geothermal energy seems reasonable, and probably would benefit due to their structure. The main thing is that the benefit is too low and the cost wayy too high. Electricity is useful in their world, but not really the way it is in ours. They're not stupid in this setting, but stuff like telephones would be hard to invent, and would also be kindof useless to most people.
Even if they had 24/7 electricity, the extent of the use would probably be limited to motors and lightbulbs, maybe a proto-telegraph like thing if they were really ingenuitive. That's a huge advantage, don't get me wrong, but even if they could build any kind of generator, the staffing would be radically expensive, and the vast majority, if not all cities wouldn't need it enough to warrant the cost, and that's assuming they COULD build a generator (which im honestly not sure enough about the mechanics to say definitively).

Mutual Appreciation Edition
previous: >>28777091

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

The OP is a WIP and any suggestions are appreciated.

resources:
General advice from Anons: https://0x0.st/onds.txt

currently we don't have any (mental) health resources.
Suggestions and debate for which to include encouraged!

I've been struggling mentally for my whole life, but especially the last year it's been feeling really heavy. I've known I wanted to be a woman instead for my entirely life, ans I've also had the hots for men, but a lot of the time, internalized transphobia has kept me from admitting I was trans, and internalized homophobia kept me from admitting that I'm attracted to men. I've really been working through that and I've pretty much come to terms with it but I still feel like I'm going crazy a lot of the time. There's still that nagging doubt and everything, you know?

I think one of the main things that's driving me crazy is trying to figure out if it's worth it for me to transition and it causes me a lot of stress trying to decide what I want to do. It feels almost like I'm trapped in limbo and that both transitioning and not transitioning are scary options but for different reasons. Another major thing that's bothering me a lot is the dysphoria itself. I'll constantly be bothered by the little things and daydreaming that it could be different and that I'm not a man, and sometimes it gets acute and strong and I feel extremely intense disgust with my body and feel hopeless and I want to die. I have a mood disorder and a sometimes crippling level of anxiety on top of it, too. I've been using drugs for the last decade to cope with it and try to make everything numb enough to be okay.

I almost came out to my parents before puberty but I decided against it because I know how stigmatized being trans was and my only exposure to trans women was just like gag characters that looked like men. I almost transitioned multiple other times but always got scared or felt too hopeless and I didn't, and I regret it, but despite the regret I still can't make myself transition. I worry a lot about passing and how people will treat me and spend a lot of time trying to decide if I could pass and driving myself crazy with that.

tl;Dr: not very fun

>>28726482
>OSR is only good for nostalgia. 5e is perfectly fine for everything but rolling for stats.
I disagree. B/X is a much more elegant game than 5e. Combat is over in 1-3 rounds and doesn't have inflated HP totals. The XP system rewards treasure hunting over combat, which synchronizes with the core dungeon crawling gameplay loop instead of wandering through a line of railroaded DM plot points. The game only has 4 human classes and 3 nonhuman races, which is all you need for classic fantasy - a city full of mushroom people isn't so mystical in 5e when you have warforged astral self monks and psionic tiefing knights at home. That, and you don't have to make charisma rolls for intimidation or persuasion which means you won't be foiled by the d20 after actually doing good roleplaying.

5e doesn't use 3d6 down the line because you need to roll skill checks for absolutely everything. Player skill is much more important in OSR.
>but it makes for a different D&D game one which modern rules and modern players just aren't built for.
I mean, it definitely makes for a different game. 5e has almost no mechanics for exploration at all, and the ones that exist are almost unplayable RAW. Personally I find dungeon crawling much more engaging when light isn't just an unlimited cantrip and your torch is a fragile safeguard between the party and a darkness full of monsters, but that's me, and I'm not exactly an old gamer who was around when this stuff was current.

posts.sub: Why should I give up all of this? Why!!?
posts.com:
I spent a week in Vegas. I stayed at a very nice hotel where rich people gravitate to. Boy, I was treated like a princess. I was wined and dined, they bought me flowers, and a guy I dated for three consecutive nights bought me a Louis Vuitton handbag before he flew back home. They (because I dated multiple guys during this week) treated me to the Cirque Du Soleil show and to other expensive shows. They were proud to be seen with me. This has NEVER happened to me when I come out as a trans woman. Not even the most open-minded guy has ever treated me like that.

There is an unfathomable difference in the way men treat me based on whether they know I am trans or they do not know I am trans.

No, they are not transphobic for not wanting to date a trans person. I see a lot of bad and disingenuous advice online. Someone can be a trans ally and still be grossed out at the idea of a trans woman.

I have to be selfish. I have to think about myself because I have always put others' needs before mine. Fuck that. Not anymore.

Yeah, yeah. I know. Someone is gonna tell me, "honey, you will find a guy who loves you for who you are." Bullshit. It has NEVER happened to me in all of these years. I have had several guys enamored with me and who have treated me like a princess, as long as they do NOT know I am trans. So, don't even try blaming my personality. There is a shift in people's perception when they know you are trans. They can't help it.

Do I sound pissed? It's because I truly am. I am pissed because I was taught to be honest and immediately come out, and that has only worked against me.

I didn't transition to be treated like a freak. I transitioned to be treated like a woman.

These guys in Vegas were super protective of me. We were walking to the show and it was cold, and they took off their coat. They kept asking me if I was okay, if I needed anything, or if I was okay walking.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
We sat to watch the show, I told them I wanted some popcorn, and they stood up in the middle of the show and went all the way to the other side of the autidotrium to get me popcorn. They spoiled me.

The best that can happen when I come out as trans is someone telling me they want to hook up in the comfort and privacy of my home. But 90% of the men I disclosed to were grossed out and left, especially after learning I was post-op.

So, no, I will keep enjoying my female privilege until it lasts. I will keep flirting with guys, I will let them spoil me. I do not lead them on. For example, one man who approached me was insistent. I told him I was not interested and that I had a boyfriend back home, but he begged me. He said he just wanted my company with no expectations. Super respectful. He took me to dinner and bought me flowers. Nobody has ever bought me flowers when I have come out as trans.
